title: MSC #7, Keystone Classic
description:
MSC #7, Keystone Classic is a part of the Mountain States Cup (MSC)-- the largest full-discipline (endurance and gravity) race series in the United States.

Saturday’s events include a cross country race and super d race. Sunday\'s events include a short track race and downhill.

Cross country, downhill and four cross are qualifiers for the 2011 USA Cycling Mountain Bike National Championships.

All racers 18 & under pay the junior entry fee. So even if you race CAT 1 15-18, make sure to register under the Junior category so you receive the best price!

Course maps will be available online at www.racemsc.com
course:
Cross Country Course Description
Start at the Keystone Ski building (NEUTRAL ROLL OUT) head out River Run Road, take a left of East Keystone Road (NEUTRAL ROLL OUT). Take a left onto Jackstraw Road and let the racing begin on the steep gravel road. At approx. the 1 mile mark, turn right onto Bluegrass singletrack, climb up Celtic Way and turn right. Head up to Let It Ride (at first it is two track and then you take another right onto Let It Ride Singletrack). Follow Let It Ride all the way to the top of the mountain to 3P Road. Turn right of 3P Road for a short little power climb at the top, turn left onto Mosquito Coast. You will follow this all the way back down to Jackstraw Road. When you hit the road, turn right and climb up Logger\'s Way. Follow Logger\'s Way to Boy Scout following it downhill (left) to Jackstraw Road where you turn right and follow it downhill for about 1/2 mile to Sleepy Hollow then onto Easy Street back to base area. Pro and CAT 1 do 2 long laps. You will turn out to do your second lap where Sleepy Hallow pops back out onto Jackstraw Road just before Easy Street. 1 lap = 9.96 miles with 1,897 feet of climbing

CAT 2 and CAT 1 15-18
1 long lap (described above) then a short lap which will be the same as the Long Loop up to where Celtic Way meets Let It Ride. Instead of turning right to head up Let It Ride, you will veer left onto Cadillac Road following it past the Gondola Mid-Station, then turn left onto Boy Scout back to Jackstraw. Turn right following the road down to Sleepy Hallow. Turn right onto Sleepy Hallow and follow to Easy Street back to the bottom of River Run to finish at the base of the Summit Express chairlift.

CAT 3 will do one long lap described in the first paragraph.

Junior 14 & Under will do one short lap described above in the second paragraph.

Super D Course Description

Start with a LeMans style start about 75 to 150 yards from the start of Girl Scout Trail. Follow Girl Scout to TNT then over to Punk Rocks, then onto Logger\'s Way to Boy Scout to Jackstraw Road, turning left onto Sleepy Hollow to East Street finishing at the base of the Summit Express Chair Lift. 5.91 miles with 2,074 feet of descending

NOTE: This course really puts the \"D\" in Super D. Be prepared for high speed and demanding terrain. It is not for the faint of heart. The Super D Course shares descending trail with Cross Country. During Saturday Super D practicve, XC racers have the right of way on Saturday during their race. 

XC START WAVES

1 long lap, 1 short lap- CAT 2 and CAT 1 15-18
1 long lap- CAT 3
1 short lap- Junior 14 & Under
2 long loops- Pro/CAT 1

Downhill Course Description

Start at Cowboy Up follow to Motorhea, to Paid in Full then onto Wild Thing to River RUn Trail finishing at he base of The Summit Express chairlift. 2.94 miles descending 2,075 feet

Short Track Description
Coming soon!
registration:
REGISTRATION

The best way to register for Keystone Classic is online here! Online registration deadline is Wednesday, July 20 at 11:59 p.m. There is no fee this year for registering online at Active.com. You can also download the Keystone Revival Registration Form. On-site race entry fees and mail-in registration form entry fees are the same. Forms mailed in must be postmarked by Saturday, July 16 or received by email to  info@racemsc.comThis e-mail address is being protected from spambots. You need JavaScript enabled to view it This e-mail address is being protected from spam bots, you need JavaScript enabled to view it no later than Wednesday, July 20 at 5 p.m. No faxes please (they just aren\'t reliable).

ON-SITE REGISTRATION

If you aren\'t able to pre-register by Wednesday at 11:59 p.m., you can still register on Friday, Saturday or Sunday. Race entry fees are here. Registration/check-in for your wave will close one hour prior to its designated start time. This includes pre-registered riders. 

* does not apply to all races. Must register by closing of registration on Saturday at 6 p.m. for all DH races. Packet pick-up for pre-registered riders may occur day-of, but must be at least 1 hour prior to start wave.

ALL riders that hold USAC licenses need to bring the license or authorization to ride with them in order to register.  Every race.  Every time.  If you forget, you can show us on a fancy phone.  No proof of license = no racy racy.  If you\'re a CAT 1 rider or Pro, you can\'t race on a one-day.

RACE ENTRY TRANSFER POLICY

If you happen to break your collar bone the week before the race, sprain a thumb, or if any other unforeseen circumstance suddenly arises, never fear, the MSC crew won\'t let you down! We\'re here to help get you back to racing! Contact us at info@racemsc.comThis e-mail address is being protected from spambots. You need JavaScript enabled to view it by the Wednesday prior to the race weekend (online registration deadline) and we\'ll gladly transfer your entry fee to any other MSC race. NO REFUNDS. Incidents during the weekend (Friday - Sunday) of the event do not count for an entry transfer. This includes injuries from practice, vehicles breaking down, your ride leaving you, sickness, losing your dog, forgetting your shoes, or anything else.
notes: All information can be found at www.racemsc.com!

HOW TO GET HERE

Keystone is located about 7 miles off of I-70. Take Exit 205 (Dillon/Silverthorne) and head east on US 6/Blue River Parkway. Continue to follow US 6 east for about 6 miles. Keystone will be on your right.

course:
ACE COURSE

Pink Loop (formally the Long loop)

The start/finish is located in the new Base Village. Riders will head up the Dawdler Work Road to the water plant and intersect the Village Bound trail. This singletrack will take riders to teh K.A.R. and then intersect the Thorton Work Road. Riders continue up this road to teh Ullrhof Restaurant where they will pick up the Cross Mountain Trail. Take the Cross Mountain Trail to Goverment Trail East, then go left down Anaerobic Nightmare.  Riders then go left on the Tom Blake Trail and take it to Faraway Road. Turn left off the paved Faraway Road for 100 yards then go right on Tom Blake Trail. Continue to Funnel Hill down to the finish. 11.4 miles. Estimated pro time for long loop = 1 hour.

Green Loop (formally the short loop)

Same as long loop until Cross Mountain Trail meets Government Trail East. Instead of taking Government Trail East, riders will head down Powerline and take a left on Tom Blake at the bottom of the Powerline DH. Regroup on the long loop and follow it to the finish. 8.7 miles

CAT 1, Pro Women and Singlespeed = 1 pink loop and 1 green loop
CAT 2 = 1 pink loop
CAT 3 and JR 14 & Under = 1 green loop

title: Boulder Escape MTB Race
description: Coming Sunday, August 28th, the new Valmont Bike Park’s first bike race, the Boulder Escape MTB Race is a cross country mtb race and part of the Boulder Mountainbike Festival (BMF).  The BMF blends the best features of the park for a jam packed day of skills, racing and big air!  The Boulder Mountainbike Alliance is partnering with the City of Boulder to create this special event as an annual fundraiser for the park. The day starts with mountain bike circuit racing for cross country enthusiasts, we add a Dual Slalom clinic followed by informal head to head Dual Slalom racing and building to the Colorado Slopestyle State Championships which will crown the final Kings and Queens for the day. Only the cross country event is sanctioned by USA Cycling. It’s a full on festival, bike games, food, jumpy castle, and maybe even some libations.  So mark your calendars now and prepare for mayhem! Sunday ,August 28th, be there.
course: The course is a mix of manicured, flowy single track (60%), two-track (30%) and dirt roads (10%).  Expert races will include technical features on singletrack.  There are two short climbs per lap totaling 100 vertical feet of climbing and the lap length is 1.8 miles.  Racers will do multiple laps racing for 40min - 1 hour depending on the category. The fastest lap times will be about 8 minutes and there are plenty of passing opportunities.
registration: Onsite race registration is available up until 20 minutes before the start.  Registration opens at 7:00am.  Only Cat 2 & 3 may race on a one day license for $5, Cat 1 and Pro must present their current annual license at registration - there will be no annual licenses available for purchase on site. Renewals are best done by going to www.usacycling.org.  Collegiate license holders can use collegiate license in Collegiate category. 2nd race is $10. Race will procede rain or shine, no refunds. Juniors race FREE (<18yrs).  All USA Cycling Mtb rules apply.
notes:
Prizes for top three of each class.  Cash for Open Men and Women classes.  *** Link to Valmont Bike Park page - http://bouldermountainbike.org ***
To sign up for Dual Slalom clinic and Slopestyle State Champs go to https://bouldermountainbike.org/civicrm/event/info?reset=1&id=31/valmontbikepark
directions:
From Denver, Take I-25 north to Highway 36 towards Boulder.  After 18 miles on Hwy 36, take Foothills Parkway exit heading north.  After 3 miles, make a right on Valmont Road. After .5 mile look for parking signs - parking is available at SE corner of Park off Valmont Road by dog park or on Airport Rd above north, past the park. 
** From Ft Collins - Take I-25 south then head west on exit 240 on Hwy 119 towards Longmont.  Continue Hwy 119 through Longmont onto the \'Diagnal\' towards Boulder. In Boulder, Hwy 119 becomes Foothills Parkway.  Turn left at Valmont Rd and head .5 miles and look for parking signs.

title: MSC #9, Sol Survivor
description:
MSC #9, Sol Survivor is a part of the Mountain States Cup (MSC)-- the largest full-discipline (endurance and gravity) race series in the United States.

Sol Survivor is the season finale for both the Gravity and Endurance Series. Saturday’s events include a four cross and super d race. Sunday\'s events include a short track and downhill, and Monday will be the cross country. All points are worth DOUBLE in the Mountain States Cup Series Overall Standings. This is the event to make or break your 2011 Overall Series Sanding.

Cross country, downhill and four cross are qualifiers for the 2011 USA Cycling Mountain Bike National Championships.

All racers 18 & under pay the junior entry fee. So even if you race CAT 1 15-18, make sure to register under the Junior category so you receive the best price!

Course maps will be available online at www.racemsc.com
course: Visit www.racemsc.com for course information.
registration:
REGISTRATION

The best way to register for Sol Survivor is online here! Online registration deadline is Wednesday, April 27 at 11:59 p.m. There is no fee this year for registering online at Active.com. Online registration deadline is Wednesday, August 31 at 11:59 p.m. You can also download the Sol Survivor Registration Form. On-site race entry fees and mail-in registration form entry fees are the same. Forms mailed in must be postmarked by Saturday, August 27 or received by email to  info@racemsc.comThis e-mail address is being protected from spambots. You need JavaScript enabled to view it This e-mail address is being protected from spambots. You need JavaScript enabled to view it no later than Wednesday, August 31 at 5 p.m. No faxes please (they just aren\'t reliable).
ON-SITE REGISTRATION

If you aren\'t able to pre-register by Wednesday at 11:59 p.m., you can still register on Friday, Saturday or Sunday. Race entry fees are here. Registration/check-in for your wave will close one hour prior to its designated start time. This includes pre-registered riders. 

* does not apply to all races. Must register by closing of registration on Saturday at 6 p.m. for all DH races. Packet pick-up for pre-registered riders may occur day-of, but must be at least 1 hour prior to start wave.

ALL riders that hold USAC licenses need to bring the license or authorization to ride with them in order to register.  Every race.  Every time.  If you forget, you can show us on a fancy phone.  No proof of license = no racy racy.  If you\'re a CAT 1 rider or Pro, you can\'t race on a one-day.
RACE ENTRY TRANSFER POLICY

If you happen to break your collar bone the week before the race, sprain a thumb, or if any other unforeseen circumstance suddenly arises, never fear, the MSC crew won\'t let you down! We\'re here to help get you back to racing! Contact us at info@racemsc.comThis e-mail address is being protected from spambots. You need JavaScript enabled to view it by the Wednesday prior to the race weekend (online registration deadline) and we\'ll gladly transfer your entry fee to any other MSC race. NO REFUNDS. Incidents during the weekend (Friday - Sunday) of the event do not count for an entry transfer. This includes injuries from practice, vehicles breaking down, your ride leaving you, sickness, losing your dog, forgetting your shoes, or anything else.
notes: All information can be found at www.racemsc.com.
directions:
SolVista Bike Park and Granby Ranch are located in the beautiful Fraser Valley, only two miles south of Granby, Colorado and 15 miles north of Fraser, Colorado on Highway US 40.

From Denver:
Take I 70 west to exit 232 for US-40 W toward Empire/Granby. You\'ll be on US-40 for about 43 miles and two miles before you enter the town of Granby, turn right at Village Road (a big City Market will be on your left). Stay on Village Road for 1.3 miles. Within the first quarter mile you\'ll pass by the Inn at Silver Creek on your left. Chances are you\'ll be staying there. Village Road will go up and over the hill and Sol Vista Basin and the SolVista Bike Park will be on your right.

From Colorado Springs:
Take I-25 N to Denver, get on I-70 W and read the above directions.

title: USGP Cyclocross- New Belgium Cup
description:
The second weekend of the USGP of Cyclocross returns to Fort Collins, CO after a wildly successful debut in 2010.  Fort Collins is home to a number of cyclocross standouts - including Georgia Gould, Meredith Miller and up and coming junior Skyler Trujillo - so the competition for hometown domination will continue to be instense

The course will feature a deceptively tough course - featuring a VERY nifty flyover, native grasses that require power, terrain and elevation changes, dirt and pavement.

Please note that there will be a $3 per car parking charge in effect on Saturday and Sunday.
course: The course will feature a deceptively tough course - featuring a VERY nifty flyover, native grasses that require power, terrain and elevation changes, dirt and pavement.
registration:
Online Registration is available here: https://www.BikeReg.com/events/register.asp?eventid=14100

Day of registration will be available and riders will be charged at $10 per race on-site registration late fee.
notes:
NOTES:

Registration
NO REFUNDS
Pre-registration mandatory for Elite Men, U-23 Men, and Elite Women only. Pre-registration encouraged for all other categories. Race-day registration will incur a one-time $10 fee.  Registration CLOSES 1 hour prior to each race\'s scheduled start time so please leave adequate time for parking and getting to registration.
Regulations:
All U.S. Gran Prix of Cyclocross Series events shall be held under the 2011 UCI regulations.
Note:  Races designated as ACA or OBRA are not sanctioned by USA Cycling. Racers in theses categories must race on an ACA or OBRA license (available at registration) For more information see Participation section below.
Participation: 
Elite Men, U23 Men, and Elite Women:
From the UCI Rule 5.1.043: The start order of events is determined as follows:

   C.   Men Elite, Elite Women, Men Under-23 and Junior Men 17-18

1. As per the most recently published UCI cyclo-cross individual classification of the current season (or the final classification of the previous season if no classification has yet been published for the current season);

2. Unclassifiedriders: by drawing lots.


(*) For unclassified riders, the start order within the team must be confirmed by the national federations during riders confirmation. Taking each nation in turn on the basis of the classification by nation of the concerned category from the world championships of the previous season, a place shall be allocated to the next rider in sequence.
Federations which do not appear in the classification by nation specified above shall, on the basis of the same rotation system, take the last places, in an order determined by drawing lots.

Procedurally, USGP staff will determine how many rows will be cordoned off and all riders, those ranked and those unranked, must remain behind this cordon. With ten (10) minutes to start, the Race Announcer will begin introducing, in the elite men\'s race, the first two (2) rows (16 riders), and, in the elite women\'s race, the front row (8 riders). These top riders will be introduced in the Finish Area and then proceed to the Start Area Grid to fill in their respective rows. Simultaneously, USGP staff will call-up the remaining rows of UCI ranked riders.  Prior to race day, all remaining registered riders without UCI ranking points will be randomly sorted and assigned a number. On race day, these unranked riders will then be called up in numerical order to fill the remaining rows.

Riders are advised to report 15 minutes before their respective start. Per UCI regulations rider call-up is a maximum of ten minutes before the start.  If riders are not present with 10 minutes to start and miss their call-up, they will lose their start grid position.



Junior Men 17/18 

Sun Prairie and Fort Collins:
Start Order for Junior 17, 18 riders will be determined by drawing lots one hour before the race.   Each Junior Rider will be allowed to draw their number based on their order of registration.  The number drawn will be their Bib / Start number. They will be called up in numerical order. Riders not present when their name is called for the drawing will draw last.

Louisville and Bend:
From the UCI Rule: 5.1.043 The start order of events is determined as follows:
      D)  Other events: Men Elite, Elite Women, Men under-23 and men juniors:

As per the most recently published UCI cyclo-cross individual classification for the
current season for the category concerned. If no classification has yet been published for the current season, the start order will be determined by the final UCI individual cyclo-cross classification for the previous season. After all UCI Classified riders, Start Order for Junior 17, 18 riders will be determined by drawing lots one hour before the race.  Each Junior Rider will be allowed to draw their number based on their order of registration.  The number drawn will be their Bib / Start number. They will be called up in numerical order. Riders not present when their name is called for the drawing will draw last.

 * Master 35+ Men
For the first two races of the 2011 series (The Planet Bike Cup), Master 35+ men will be called up based on the 2010 USGP Masters 35+ ranking - ONLY PRE-REGISTERED RIDERS WILL BE INCLUDED FOR CALL-UP POSITION.
For all subsequent races, all Masters 35+ men will be called up in order of the latest USGP ranking (PRE-REGISTERED RIDERS ONLY).  NEW Rankings are posted on MONDAY following each USGP race weekend. 

One row of eight (8) remaining Masters 35+ men with points from host venue\'s regional/local series will then be called up. Start order will be the same for both Saturday and Sunday of a given USGP race weekend.   All other riders will be called up by order of registration. Published Regional Series standings from the Monday preceeding the USGP will be used.  (Madison - MadCross; Louisville - OVCX; Ft Collins - Cross Cup; Bend - Top 3 each from Cross Crusade, MFG Cross, Seattle Cup)

Masters 45+ Men:  
At the first two races of the 2011 series (The Planet Bike Cup), Master 45+ Men will be called up based on the 2009 USGP Masters 45+ ranking  - ONLY PRE-REGISTERED RIDERS WILL BE CONSIDERED FOR CALL-UP POSITION.

Any riders who were ranked in the 2009 USGP Masters 35+ Series will be given that equivalent ranking in the Masters 45+ for the first two races (The Planet Bike Cup) ONLY PRE-REGISTERED RIDERS WILL BE CONSIDERED FOR CALL-UP POSITION.

For all subsequent races, all PRE-REGISTERED  Masters 45+ Men will be called up in order of the latest USGP ranking.  NEW rankings are posted on MONDAY following each USGP weekend. 

One row of eight (8) PRE-REGISTERED  Masters 45+ Men with points from the host venue\'s local/regional series will then be called up.  Start order will be the same for both Saturday and Sunday of a given USGP race weekend.   All other riders will be called up by order of registration. Published Regional Series standings from the Monday preceeding the USGP will be used.  (Madison - MadCross; Louisville - OVCX; Ft Collins - Cross Cup; Bend - Top 3 each from Cross Crusade, MFG Cross, Seattle Cup)

* All non-USGP category events (Cat 4 Men, Women 1/2/3, Cat 3/4 Women, Junior 10-16, Cat 2/3 Men, Singlespeed and Masters 55+):

Start Order for these categories will be determined by order of registration.


Series Classification: 
Points shall be awarded according to the series points schedule. 
All rider\'s results shall be counted towards the final classification. 
In the event of a tie on individual classification, the best placing in the most recent event shall be decisive.
For more information see our website at http://www.usgpcyclocross.com.

title: Colorado Mesa University  Mountain Bike Race
USA Cycling Development Camp Managers Meeting
Fall Back Cross Race
description:
Join us for the inaugural Fall Back Cross race.  It will be held when Daylight Saving Time ends so be sure to set your clock back.  Heck, set two clocks back to make sure you\'ll be on time.  Your results from this race will count toward your cyclo-cross ranking which will be used for call ups at this year\'s Cyclo-cross National Championships in Madison, WI.  Your ranking will also be used for call-ups at this race!

Hotel rooms for $65, without tax, while available at the Hyatt Summerfield Suites right across the parking lot.  Rooms have full kitchen and they offer free breakfast!  Call 719 268-9990 and say you are with USA Cycling to get this great rate while they are available!
course: Course is primarily grass, sand/dirt, with a start and finish on pavement. It is was also designed with input from Katie and Mark Compton. So expect to be challenged!
registration: First race is $35 and additional races are $20.  Junior races are $15.  On-site registration fee $5.  Goodie bags for first 200 pre-registered!  USA Cycling annual license, road or mountain, required for all categories except those open to Cat 4 Men and Women.  Categories open to Cat 4 Men and Women can purchase a USA Cycling one-day license.  Which means singlespeed, masters, juniors and Cat 4 M, Cat 3/4 W, 1st time W can race on a one-day.  USA Cycling racing licenses, both one-day ($10) and annual ($60) available online at www.usacycling.org/register/2011-3022. On-site registration will open at 7:00 a.m. and will close 20 minutes before each start.  No refunds will be given.
notes:
Race held rain, shine, snow, or hail. Isn\'t that what cross is all about?!

Any proceeds will go to the USA Cycling Development Foundation.

We\'re also having a first time women\'s category for those that want to try a cross race without the intimidation factor!

Bring the kids as well, we\'ll be having a free Fall Back Little Belgium for the kids and a Strider Cup event for the toddlers.  Schedule can be found at http://www.usacycling.org/events/flyer.php?permit=2011-3655.

Pint from Bristol brewery, on-site, for registered riders of age!
directions: I-25 to Rockrimmon exit.  Take Rockrimmon west to Delmonico Dr. Right onto USA Cycling Point.
